## Pick a template

Three templates ship at [`changes/_templates/`](changes/_templates/). Pick the one closest to the work; if it's a hybrid (e.g. story that fixed bugs along the way), use the closer-fitting template and add bug subsections inline.

| Work type | Template | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| Bug fix | [`changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_bugfix.md`](changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_bugfix.md) | Defect, regression, production incident, unexpected behavior. Heavy on root-cause + symptom timeline. |
| Story / feature / requirement | [`changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_story.md`](changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_story.md) | New functionality, ticket-driven work, business-requested capability. Heavy on requirements + acceptance criteria. |
| Refactor / tech-debt / optimization | [`changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_refactor.md`](changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_refactor.md) | Internal restructuring, performance work, code cleanup, no user-visible behavior change. Heavy on functional-parity proof + behavioral invariants. |
| Retrieve audit | [`changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_retrieve.md`](changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_retrieve.md) | After running the org-wide mirror retrieve described in [`docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md`](../../docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md). Snapshot record of what changed in the org since the last mirror, with suspicion-analysis heuristics. **Saves at `changes/git/retrieve-<YYYY-MM-DD>-<HHMM>-<sandbox-alias>.md`** instead of the usual `changes/<slug>.md` path. Phase 3 of the runbook covers the exact workflow including the two-commit pattern. |

Copy the template:

```bash
cp changes/_templates/_TEMPLATE_<type>.md changes/<short-kebab-slug>.md
```

