## Two-commit strategy (mandatory)

**Always two commits. Code first, doc second.** This keeps the code change reviewable on its own and lets the doc reference the exact commit hash it documents.

### Step 1 — Stage code only (selective staging — parallel-agent safe)

**Stage ONLY the files YOU touched.** Other agents (or the user, or scheduled jobs) may be working in the same repo concurrently. Blanket-adding whole directories silently grabs their in-flight changes and mangles their commits.

#### ❌ DO NOT do this

```bash
# Forbidden — sweeps in EVERYTHING modified in those directories, including
# files another agent is mid-edit on. Even if you "know" you're alone, get
# in the habit of explicit staging — sandboxes are shared, automation runs
# in the background, and your future self might be working in two tabs.
git add force-app/ scripts/ manifest/ config/
```

#### ✓ DO this — name every file explicitly

```bash
# Stage the exact files you intentionally modified.
git add force-app/main/default/classes/MyClass.cls \
        force-app/main/default/classes/MyClass.cls-meta.xml \
        manifest/my-feature.xml

# Then sanity-check: ONLY your files should be staged, nothing else.
git status -s
```

If `git status` shows other modified files you didn't touch (`M force-app/main/default/lwc/someOtherCmp/...`), **leave them alone**. They belong to another piece of work. Your commit must NOT include them.

#### Recovering "what did I touch?" if you lost track

```bash
# Working-tree changes since the last commit (everything you've edited):
git diff --name-only

# Or, if some of your work is already staged:
git diff --name-only --cached
git diff --name-only HEAD
```

Cross-reference the result against your own change log (the chat history, the manifest you're about to deploy, the file paths you've been editing). When in doubt, ask the user — better than committing a file that wasn't yours.

#### Exception: org-wide retrieve audit

The retrieve audit workflow ([`docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md`](../../docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md)) follows its OWN staging rules — by design it commits the entire mirrored `force-app/` snapshot as a single "mirror" commit, then the audit doc as the second commit. Don't try to subdivide a retrieve commit into per-file stages; the whole-org snapshot IS the unit of work. Phase 3 of the retrieve runbook covers the exact pattern (`mirror(<alias>): sync from <alias> @ ...` + `docs(retrieve): audit ...`).

For every OTHER kind of work, the selective-staging rule above is non-negotiable.

### Step 2 — Commit code with multi-line message

Use a HEREDOC so the message formats correctly:

```bash
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
<subject line, max 72 chars, imperative mood, no period>

<paragraph 1: what changed and why, in plain English>

<bullet list of every meaningful sub-change, e.g.
  - <File or component>: <one-line change>
  - <File or component>: <one-line change>
>

<paragraph 2 if needed: any caveats, temporary changes, drift>
EOF
)"
```

### Step 3 — Capture the commit hash

```bash
git log -1 --format='%H%n%h%n%s'
```

The short hash (line 2 of output) is what you embed in the doc's header block and in §13 (or whichever is the "Deploy IDs and commit references" section).

### Step 4 — Author the doc

Copy a template (per the table above), fill it in, embed the short hash from step 3 in the header block.

### Step 5 — Commit the doc separately

```bash
git add changes/<slug>.md
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
docs: <short-title-of-the-work> (refs <short-hash-from-step-3>)

<one-paragraph summary of what the doc covers>

Saved at changes/<slug>.md.
Code commit referenced: <short-hash>.
EOF
)"
```

### Step 6 — Verify both commits and clean tree

```bash
git log -2 --format='%H%n  %h  %s%n'
git status -s
```

Report both hashes back to the user.

### Variant — retrieve audits

For the **retrieve audit** template, the same two-commit pattern applies but the "code" commit is a mirror snapshot (the retrieved metadata diff), not a feature change. The full workflow with the exact commit-message subjects (`mirror(<alias>): sync from <alias> @ …` and `docs(retrieve): audit … (refs <hash>)`) lives in [`docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md`](../../docs/sf-org-mirror-retrieve.md) Phase 3. Use that recipe rather than this one.

