## Anti-patterns

### Intake-time anti-patterns

- **Starting code without a confirmed ticket number.** Even if the user "just wants this small thing", run Step A of the intake protocol first. Two minutes of confirmation is cheaper than two hours of misbuilt scope.
- **Treating a screenshot as the source of truth.** Screenshots break — when trackers migrate, when PR review tools strip images, when reviewers don't open Jira. Transcribe to text immediately (Step B) and have the user confirm the transcription. The text is the source of truth.
- **Letting "see attached screenshot" land in the changes doc.** §3 of the doc must contain the actual AC text. If you find yourself writing "see attached image", go back and finish Step B.
- **Silently fixing the ticket number after a typo / wrong read.** If you misread the ticket on first attempt, STOP and re-read-back to the user. Don't paper over by quietly correcting it in the next message.
- **Skipping the out-of-scope question** when the user gives ACs without explicit non-goals. Always ask (Step C). Out-of-scope clarity prevents the most common review-time argument: "why didn't you also do X?"

### Wrap-up-time anti-patterns

- **Skipping the doc because "the commit message says it all."** Commit messages don't have rollback procedures, verification matrices, or open follow-ups. The doc does.
- **Inlining the doc into the same commit as the code.** Breaks the two-commit guarantee; reviewers can't separate code review from doc review.
- **Stub sections** — `<TODO>` or `<...>` left in a finished doc. If a section truly doesn't apply, write `n/a` with a one-line reason.
- **Renaming the templates** — keep the `_TEMPLATE_<type>.md` naming so they sort to the top of the folder and are clearly distinct from real docs.
- **Forgetting to delete the `<!-- ... -->` guidance comments** when you fill in a template. The final doc should be clean prose.
- **Using a ticket number as the doc filename.** Ticket numbers expire when trackers migrate; the filename should describe the work.
- **Rewriting the ACs at wrap-up time** from memory or from the original screenshot, instead of pasting the intake transcription verbatim. The whole point of the intake step was to lock the agreed text down before code touched the keyboard.

### Parallel-agent / staging anti-patterns

- **`git add force-app/`** (blanket-add a top-level dir) when another agent or human might be active in the repo. Use selective staging — name every file explicitly. The only documented exception is the org-wide retrieve workflow.
- **Including someone else's file in your commit "because it was already modified".** If you didn't touch it, leave it. Either the original author will commit it later, or it's churn that doesn't belong to you.
- **Quietly reverting another agent's in-flight edit** by checking out HEAD on files you don't recognise. If files are dirty when you arrive, ask the user — never silently revert.

### Doc-content / package-manifest anti-patterns

- **Missing `**Manifest:**` line in the header block** when the work involved a `--manifest` deploy/retrieve. The doc must name the manifest file and inline its XML content in the Deploy IDs section. Reviewers shouldn't have to open a second file to know what was deployed.
- **Skipping the "Key changes — diff highlights" section** for OmniScripts / IPs / DRs / FlexiPages / layouts. The raw `git diff` for those is unreadable; the doc must surface the meaningful change.
- **Including the entire 500-line Apex file in a diff fence**. For changes that big, use line-range + method-name commentary (see "Large changes" pattern above), not a 500-line code dump.

### Same-thread / multi-doc anti-patterns

- **Spawning a new `changes/<slug>.md` for each iteration** of the same fix. Use ONE doc for the thread; update the Revision log + add a new Diff-highlights row + append the new commit hash to the header. Multiple small docs fragment the history.
- **Letting the doc's TL;DR fall behind reality** when iterating. After each new code commit on the same thread, restate §1 to describe the CUMULATIVE state of the fix, not just what the latest commit did.
- **Deleting a superseded approach from the Revision log** so the doc "reads cleaner". Mark it `(superseded by <hash>)` and leave it; the path matters to the next person who hits the same problem.

---

## Self-application

This ruleset itself was added in a single code commit — no `changes/` doc was written for it (avoiding chicken-and-egg recursion when the rule didn't yet exist). Every subsequent piece of Salesforce work in this repo (and any repo that adopts this rule) MUST follow the rule.
